members.docComment:
/**
 * Factory function to create a prismy compatible middleware. Accepts selectors to help with testing, DI etc.
 *
 * @remarks
 *
 * Selectors must be a tuple (`[Selector<string>, Selector<number>]`) not an array (`Selector<string>|Selector<number>[] `). Be careful when declaring the array outside of the function call.
 *
 * Be carefuly to remember the mhandler is a function which returns an _async_ function. Not returning an async function can lead to strange type error messages.
 *
 * Another reason for long type error messages is not having `{"strict": true}` setting in tsconfig.json or not compiling with --strict.
 *
 * @param selectors - Tuple of selectors
 *
 * @param mhandler - Middleware handler
 *
 * @returns A prismy compatible middleware
 *
 * @example
 *
 * Simple Example
 * ```ts
 *
 * const withCors = middleware([], next => async () => {
 *  const resObject = await next()
 *
 *  return updateHeaders(resObject, {
 *    'access-control-allow-origin': '*'
 *  })
 * })
 *
 * ```
 *
 * @public
 */
members.name: middleware

members.docComment:
/**
 * Generates a handler to be used by http.Server
 *
 * @remarks
 *
 * Selectors must be a tuple (`[Selector<string>, Selector<number>]`) not an array (`Selector<string>|Selector<number>[] `). Be careful when declaring the array outside of the function call.
 *
 * @param selectors - Tuple of Selectors to generate arguments for handler
 *
 * @param handler - Business logic handling the request
 *
 * @param middlewareList - Middleware to pass request and response through
 *
 * @example
 * ```ts
 * const worldSelector: Selector<string> = () => "world"!
 *
 * export default prismy([ worldSelector ], async world => {
 *  return res(`Hello ${world}!`) // Hello world!
 * })
 * ```
 *
 * @public
 */
members.name: prismy
